<li id="cite_note-FreehlingBook1-37">^ <a href="#cite_ref-FreehlingBook1_37-0" title=""><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-FreehlingBook1_37-1" title=""><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-FreehlingBook1_37-2" title=""><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> William W. Freehling, The Road to Disunion: Secessionists at Bay 1776-1854, pages 17- 19. Freehling also said that as of 1850, 21 percent of border state blacks were free, as opposed to two percent in the lower South, and that over half of the South's manufactured goods were made in the border states, while less than a fifth of the total was produced in the lower South.</li>
